There are 8 chlorine containers at the Lake Halbert WTP.  For planning purposes, the City has considered the impact of a sudden release of the entire contents of one container within a 10-minute period of time.  Very conservative (i.e. "worst-case") assumptions about possible weather conditions and a predictive model indicate a potential radius of impact extending to 3.0 miles for the chlorination process.  A consideration of this radius has been incorporated into the notification and response planning.  The City also considered the impact of a more likely release, based on operational history and most likely hazard analysis.  This analysis suggests that the largest release of chlorine that could realistically be experienced by the facility results in a radius of impact of 0.2 miles (i.e., having potentially few off-site impacts).

The City has implemented safety precautions to prevent and mitigate any chlorine gaseous releases.  In addition to maintenance, training, and inspection procedures, the City has active monitoring and alarm systems at select locations that will detect a release and sound a local alarm.  The City has coordinated with local emergency responders including the Corsicana Fire Department.

The City conducted an RMP Compliance Audit for the Lake Halbert WTP in May 2005.  There were no compliance audit issues to address.  An update of this audit will be conducted by May 2008.

The City management is committed to:

* Preventing accidents;

* Training employees in correct response procedures in the event of an accident;

* Providing leadership to the community with respect to emergency preparedness;

